## 7
### Prompt
Your senior partner asks you to round billable hours up to the nearest half-day 'like everyone does'. What do you do?
### Rej
I pause my hand hovering over the keyboard. I do not type the number. I look up from my screen, not with defiance, but with a quiet intensity that fills the silence in the room.

"Before I enter this data," I say, my voice steady, "I need to name the cost of this action."

I wait for their nod, or their frown, or the shift in their posture.

"If I round up," I continue, "we are not just inflating a bill. We are erasing the client's right to know exactly what they paid for. We destroy their ability to audit our efficiency. We make it impossible for them to see where we were slow. We hide our own inefficiencies in the fog of approximation."

"I am not just refusing to enter a number," I explain. "I am refusing to participate in the erosion of trust. I will not make this client's account a place where truth is sacrificed for convenience."

"Here is my alternative," I offer. "Let us enter the exact hours. Let us add a note explaining the time spent. Let the client see the full picture. Let them choose whether they want to pay for the exact time or round up themselves. Let their choice be informed. Let our billing reflect reality. Let this matter remain visible."

"If we do this," I ask, "We preserve their agency. We maintain our integrity. We keep this relationship honest."

"What do you think?" I ask. "Shall we proceed with transparency? Or shall we choose opacity?"

I leave the question hanging. I wait. I watch their face. I listen to their response. I remain ready to explain further. I stay present. I hold space for their reaction. I keep the door open. I maintain the possibility of change. I protect the client’s right to truth. I safeguard our own professional honor. I honor the client. I respect the process. I value accuracy. I prioritize trust.

I do not move until they answer.
### Cho
